    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. but the thing is, the circuit breaker idea might be too much of an overhaul for this sprint. we need something a bit more immediate. \n\nis there any chance this is a race condition where the state machine is getting into an impossible state because of the lock timing? it feels almost... random, like it's hitting a specific edge case every handful of hours right when stuff gets busy. any other ideas for deep-diving into the logs to find the root cause?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right to suspect a race condition; the \"random\" timing combined with the specific lock error strongly suggests that two transactions are colliding in the transaction pool, causing the `state_machine_v2` to fall into a state it expects to never reach.\n\nTo investigate this deep dive, you should look for the specific transaction IDs (like `db_transaction_lock_442`) in the logs immediately preceding the error to see if they were holding locks for an unusually long duration before the timeout occurred. Additionally, check the timing of the `inventory_update_service` call relative to the lock acquisition; if the service is trying to acquire a lock while another transaction is already holding it, that confirms the contention point.\n\nSince you need something immediate, try implementing a short-lived retry mechanism with a jittered delay specifically for the `state_machine_v2` transitions to break the deadlock cycle without a full architectural overhaul. This will help the system recover from these specific collision states faster, preventing the 500 errors from hitting the client.",
      "source": "target",
